{] The Queen's Gambit Declined is truly a lifetime opening.
Like no other it passed the test of centuries of chess practice. This opening
was employed by almost all old maestros including Morphy, Chigorin and
Steinitz as well as by modern super grandmasters like Carlsen, Ananda, Caruana
and many others. Different move orders were popular at different times. If in
the old days it was considered safe to allow the Carlsbad Variation after 1.d4
Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 d5, nowadays most modern maestros tend to avoid typical
Carlsbad pawn chains with Black and opt for 3...d5 only in response to 3.Nf3.
Strangely enough, yours truly almost never played Queen's Gambit Declined with
Black. Nevertheless, I suppose that it perfectly suits my style and chess
philosophy. In this database, I decided to analyse Queen's Gambit Declined
from Black's point of view and chose the most straightforward way to challenge
the main move 5.Bf4 (after 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 d5 4.Nc3 Be7 5.Bf4) with 6...
c5!?. At some point, this move was a bit in the shadow of the solid 6...Nbd7
but recently it began to gain popularity again thanks to top GMs Nakamura,
Caruana and Anand first of all.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4
{In this chapter, we shall take a look at some White's attempts to avoid the
main lines. Nevertheless, one of the advantages of this line for Black is that
White's choices are highly restricted.} ({Although the move 5.Bg5 is not a
topic of the current database, we are going to examine an attempt to enter the
systems with Bf4 after provoking ...h7-h6.} 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bf4 $5 {In the future,
White will try to prove that ...h7-h6 is weakening the kingside. This idea has
been tried by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen.} c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. e3 O-O 9.
a3 Nc6 10. Qc2 {Almost by force we arrive to our main line but with the
inclusion of the move ...h7-h6. Now White will try to prove that it weakens
the black king. In his game against Kovalev, Magnus was able to prove it very
convincingly. That's why I suggest to deviate from this game and play the
logical} Qe7 $1 {Since Black has played ...h7-h6, White can not pin the
f6-knight.} ({Kovalev opted for} 10... Nh5 {However, after} 11. Bg3 dxc4 (11...
Qa5 12. O-O-O) 12. Bxc4 Be7 13. Ba2 a6 14. Rd1 Qa5 15. Bb1 $40 {White's attack
proved to be very dangerous. 1-0 (37) Carlsen,M (2872)-Kovalev,V (2660) Wijk
aan Zee 2020}) 11. b4 {Almost forced. Otherwise, Black has a strong initiative.
} (11. Rd1 e5 {[%cal Gc6d4,Ge7e1] A thematic idea in such positions allowing
Black to make use of the opposition along the e-file.} ({Another possibility
would be} 11... Rd8 $5 12. b4 e5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. bxc5 Bg4 15. Nxd5 Qxc5 16.
Nxf6+ gxf6 17. f3 Be6 $132 {With a dangerous initiative.}) 12. Bg3 Nd4 $1 {
Remember this typical sacrifice. After} 13. exd4 exd4+ 14. Ne2 dxc4 $44 {
Black has a tremendous compensation for the piece.}) ({The IQP position
arising after} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Na4 Bd6 $11 {is favourable for Black since he
is better development while White does not have good control of the d4-square.}
) ({The advantages of the move ...h7-h6 can be seen in the line} 11. O-O-O e5 {
With a pawn on h7, White would have played Bg5 in this position. After} 12. Bg3
dxc4 13. Bxc4 Be6 $15 {Black is already better. The open c-file gives him a
very nice queenside counterplay.}) 11... e5 $1 {Once again, Black makes use of
the insertion of the move ...h7-h6.} 12. bxc5 $8 {This seems to be the only
move.} ({Simply bad is} 12. Bg3 {as Black has a very strong sequence} d4 $1 13.
Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Nxb4 $1 15. axb4 Bxb4+ {Black has two pawns and a decisive
attack for the piece. I provide some lines to justify this evaluation.} 16. Kd1
(16. Nd2 Bg4 {[%cal Gf8c8]} 17. Be2 Rfc8 18. Qb1 Bxd2+ 19. Kxd2 Bf5 $1 $17)
16... Bg4 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4,Ga8c8]} 17. Qe4 (17. h3 Rac8 18. Qb1 Bh5 $40) 17...
Bc3 18. Qxg4 f5 $1 {An important intermediate move.} ({The immediate} 18...
Bxa1 $4 {runs into} 19. d6) 19. Qh4 Qb4 $1 20. Bd3 (20. Rc1 e4 21. Nxd4 Rac8
22. Nc2 Qb3 $19) 20... Bxa1 21. Bxe5 Qa3 $1 22. Ke2 Qa2+ 23. Kd1 Rac8 24. Qg3
Rf7 $19) 12... exf4 13. Nxd5 {Again, the only move allowing White to maintain
the balance.} ({After} 13. cxd5 $2 fxe3 14. dxc6 exf2+ 15. Kxf2 Ng4+ 16. Kg3
Qc7+ $19 {Black is winning on the spot.}) 13... Qxc5 14. Nxf4 {Now black has a
choice between two ideas. I believe in both cases he has enough compensation
for the pawn.} Rd8 {This is more natural from a human perspective.} ({A decent
alternative is} 14... g5 $5 15. Nd3 Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Be6 17. c5 Qxd2+ 18. Nxd2 Rfd8
19. Rc1 Rd7 $44 {Black has better structure and advantage in the development.
White's extra pawn is not important in this position.}) 15. Be2 Qa5+ {It is
important to prevent White from castling.} 16. Kf1 Bf5 17. Qb2 Rd7 $44 18. h3
Rad8 19. Rc1 Be4 $132 {Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn.})
5... O-O 6. Qc2 ({After} 6. a3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. e3 {we transpose
to the main line.}) 6... c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. cxd5 {This is the only independent
continuation.} ({After} 8. e3 Nc6 {, we have a transposition to the main line.}
) 8... Nxd5 $5 {The most principled.} (8... exd5 {looks solid as well but it
turns out that White has some pressure. For instance, :} 9. e3 Nc6 10. Be2 d4 11.
Rd1 Qb6 $1 ({The active} 11... Nb4 $6 {does not work quite well for Black.
White can play} 12. Qd2 $1 {When Black's pieces are hanging.} (12. Qb1 $6 {
1/2 (38) Edouard,R (2640)-Heimann,A (2609) Switzerland 2019}) 12... Nbd5 13.
Nxd4 Nxf4 14. exf4 $14 {In this position, the bishop pair is not sufficient
compensation for the pawn.}) 12. exd4 Bxd4 13. O-O {White's pieces are a bit
better placed in this symmetrical position. My analysis shows that despite
being very close, Black cannot achieve complete equality.} Qc5 ({Another
option is} 13... Be6 14. Ng5 Nb4 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. Qb3 $14 {when Black's minor
pieces lack stability.}) 14. Qc1 Re8 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bd3 Bg4 17. Rd2 Nd5 18.
Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Qc3 Rac8 20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Qxd4 Qxd4 22. Rxd4 Rc2 23. f3 Be6 24.
Rf2 $14) 9. Nxd5 (9. Rd1 Qb6 10. e3 Nxf4 11. exf4 Nc6 $11) 9... Qxd5 10. a3 Be7
11. Rd1 Qf5 $1 {In the endgame, Black has nothing to worry about. For example,
after} 12. Qxf5 exf5 13. e3 Nc6 14. Bb5 Be6 $11 {, the position is completely
equal.} *

