} 9... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] White can temporarily avoid the exchange of the
queens by playing} 10. Bd3 {In this structure, White can often take the
initiative my playing moves like Ne4 or e3-e4-e5. Even though Black can force
the exchange of queens by means of} Nc6 11. O-O Nb4 {, the undeveloped
queenside will continue to cause problems. For instance:} 12. Bb1 Qxd1 13. Rxd1
Nbd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Be4 Nf6 16. Nd2 $1 $14 {Black did not manage to
equalize in the game 1-0 (87) Aronian,L (2792)-Nakamura,H (2791) Saint Louis
2016.}) 10. Rxd1 Bb4 $1 {A very typical way of handling this kind of endgame
structures. Black is ready to give the bishop pair to his opponent in order to
obtain a better pawn structure.} 11. O-O {The most natural continuation.} ({
