14. Bb5 f6 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8e6] Important positional move. After giving the
dark-squared bishop away, Black is planning to put his central pawns on dark
squares. Moreover, the ...e6-e5 would solve the only issue in Black's position
- the problematic c8-bishop. The game Aronian - Anand went} 15. Bd6 Rd8 16.
Rfd1 Rxd6 17. Rxd6 Nxd6 18. Rxd6 Kf7 $1 {[%cal Gf7e7] One more precise move.
Black is sacrificing a pawn in order to achieve a favourable endgame.} 19. Bxc6
Ke7 20. Bxb7 Bxb7 {In such positions, with pawns on both wings, the bishop is
superior to the knight. Furthermore, in this concrete position, White has also
a bad pawn structure.} 21. Rd4 Rc8 ({Another option would have been} 21... e5
22. Rh4 h6 $132) 22. Rb4 Bd5 23. Ra4 Rxc3 24. Rxa7+ Kf8 25. h3 Rc1+ 26. Kh2 Rc2
27. Kg3 Rxa2 28. Rxa2 Bxa2 $11 {1/2 (30) Aronian,L (2785)-Anand,V (2779)
London 2016}) 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6] A thematic idea in such
positions. Black is planning to exchange the light-squared bishops via a6.
White should play energetically in order not to find himself in a difficult
position due to the vulnerable structure.} ({Another way to equalize would be} 
12... Nc6 $5 13. Bd6 Rd8 14. Be7 Rxd1 15. Rxd1 Nd5 16. Bb4 Ndxb4 17. cxb4 Kf8
18. a3 Ke7 $11) 13. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5] The knight is heading to b5.} ({After} 
13. Bd6 Re8 14. Bb5 Bd7 $11 {The position is equal. 1/2 (37) Adhiban,B (2671)
