Bd3 $2 {when after} h6 14. Nf3 (14. g4 $2 d4 $19) 14... dxc4 15. Bxc4 b5 $17 {
Black is going to continue with ...Bb7 followed by ...b5-b4. The attack seems
to be decisive.}) 13... d4 $5 {This is a dynamical approach to the position.} (
{A decent alternative is} 13... h6 $5 14. cxd5 exd5 15. f3 Bd6 $1 {Just in
time, Black manages to exchange White's most valuable pieces - the
dark-squared bishop.} 16. Bxd6 ({After} 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Qxd5 18. Bc4
hxg5 19. Bxd5 gxf4 $17 {Black is the one who has material advantage.}) 16...
Rxd6 17. Kb1 Qc5 18. Bd3 Rd8 $132 19. Nxf7 $6 Kxf7 20. g5 Ng8 $17 {White does
not have enough compensation for the piece.}) 14. Nce4 Nxg4 $1 {It looks a but
risky but in fact it's rather White who is in danger.} 15. c5 $8 {[%cal Ge4d6]
Only move.} ({In case of} 15. Bd6 f5 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. Bh3 d3 {Black is
winning. 0-1 (17) Peschardt,S (2231)-Limbert,N (2175) ICCF email 2011}) 15...
h6 16. Nd6 $8 hxg5 17. hxg5 g6 18. Nxf7 ({The alternative} 18. Bd3 {fails to}
Bxd6 19. Bxd6 Rxd6 20. cxd6 Qxg5 $17 {and Black is almost winning.}) 18... d3
$1 (18... Qxc5 19. Bc4 $13) 19. Bxd3 (19. Rxd3 $2 Qe1+ $19) 19... Rxd3 20. Rxd3
Qxc5 {Black is not at risk. The following lines justify this evaluation.} 21.
Rc3 (21. Nh6+ Nxh6 22. Qxc5 Bxc5 23. gxh6 Kh7 24. Bg5 Ne5 25. Rc3 Bb6 26. Bf4
Nc6 $15) 21... Qf5 22. Nd6 Qxc2+ 23. Rxc2 e5 24. Nxc8 Rxc8 25. Bg3 Bxg5 26. Rc4
Nh6 27. Bxe5 Rf8 $15 {Once again, Black is fighting for an advantage.}) 12...
Rd8 13. g4 {The most principled continuation.} ({Long time ago, White was
often going for the following sequence:} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Bd3 Bg4 15. Ng5 {
Now, Black can more or less force the draw by playing a sequence of pretty
natural moves.} Bxd1 16. Bxh7+ Kf8 17. Rxd1 d4 18. Qb3 Nd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20.
Qxd5 Rxd5 21. Be4 Rd7 22. Nf3 Rad8 23. Bf5 Rd5 24. e4 Rb5 25. Bc7 Bxa3 26. Bxd8
Rxb2+ 27. Ka1 Nb4 28. Nxd4 Ra2+ 29. Kb1 Rb2+ $11 {With a perpetual.}) 13... e5
$5 {This is a new move.} ({In a few correspondence games, White had the
initiative. Here is an example:} 13... dxc4 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Bxc4 Nxg4 (15...
e5 16. g5) 16. Ng5 Nf6 17. Nce4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 g6 19. Rd1 $44 {White has a
strong initiative for the pawn. Black's position is practically very difficult.
1-0 (50) Raessler,A (2331)-Narciso,M (2207) ICCF email 2015}) 14. g5 (14. Nxe5
Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxg4 $15) 14... Ne4 $1 {This is the point. Black is in a very
good shape in the arising complications.} 15. Nxe5 {The critical reply.} ({
After} 15. Bxe5 Bf5 16. Bd3 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Nxc3+ 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Bxd3+
20. Rxd3 dxc4 $11 {The position is equal.}) 15... Nxc3+ 16. Qxc3 Bf5+ 17. Ka1
Qa4 $1 {The most precise continuation. Black practically foces the draw.} ({
After} 17... Qxc3 18. bxc3 Nxe5 19. Bxe5 Be4 20. Rg1 Bxa3 21. cxd5 Bxd5 22. Be2
{Black is close to equality but still it is White who can try to play for a
win here.}) 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 ({After} 20. Bxe5 dxc4 21.
Rxd8+ (21. Rd4 b5) 21... Rxd8 22. Bd4 (22. Bxg7 $4 Rd3) 22... g6 $132 {, Black
has nothing to worry about.}) 20... dxc4 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Qxe7 Rd1+ 23. Rxd1
Qxd1+ 24. Ka2 Qb3+ $11) ({In a recent game, Mamedyarov tried} 11. Rg1 {when
Black's most logical reaction is} a6 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5] with the idea to
answer} 12. g4 {with} dxc4 13. Bxc4 b5 {The following moves seem pretty
logical -} 14. g5 Nh5 15. Bd3 b4 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Be4 bxc3 18. Bxc6 {Nakamura
played OK as well but the following option is more straightforward and
principled} Bxa3 $5 ({The game saw} 18... cxb2+ 19. Kb1 {with an unclear
position.1/2 (44) Mamedyarov,S (2764)-Nakamura,H (2743) Saint Louis 2019}) 19.
Rd4 $8 {The only saving move for White!} cxb2+ 20. Kb1 Bb4 $1 21. Qa4 (21. Kxb2
e5 $5 (21... Nxf4 $5 22. Rxf4 Bc3+ 23. Kc1 Qa1+ 24. Qb1 Qxb1+ 25. Kxb1 Rb8+ 26.
Kc2 Ba5 $132) 22. Bxe5 Be6 $40) 21... Qxa4 22. Bxa4 Nxf4 23. Rxb4 Ne2 24. Bc2 {
White has no more then perpetual -} Nxg1 25. Rh4+ Kg8 26. Bh7+ Kh8 $11) 11...
dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. g5 exf4 14. gxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Ne7 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Rhg1+
Kh8 18. Qe4 {So far, everything was pretty forced. With his last move, White
wants to bring his queen into the attack.} ({The alternatives are harmless.
For example, after} 18. e4 b5 19. Bd5 Nxd5 20. exd5 Bd7 {Black's queenside
play shouldn't be underestimated.} 21. Kb1 b4 22. Qd2 Qb6 23. Qxb4 Qxb4 24.
axb4 a5 $132 {Black has more than sufficient counterplay.}) ({The move} 18. Nd4
{does not create concrete threats. Hence, Black has time to organize his own
counterplay. After} fxe3 19. fxe3 Qe5 (19... Bf5 $5) 20. Kb1 Bf5 21. Nxf5 Nxf5
22. Rd5 Nxe3 23. Rxe5 Nxc2 24. Re4 f5 25. Re7 Nd4 26. Rxb7 Nf3 27. Rg2 Ne5 $13
{, the position is equal.}) 18... Ng6 19. Qd4 Qb6 $1 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Rd6 Bh3
$1 {This move was invented in pre-computer era in 1993 by Ukrainian GM Yuri
Kruppa and approved nowadays by all top engines. Black is freeing the
c8-square for the rook. The is the active way to parry Black's threat.} 22. Bd5
({After} 22. Kb1 Rac8 ({Another good option is} 22... Bf5+ 23. Ka2 Be4 24. Bd5
Bxd5+ 25. Rxd5 Rad8 {when Black has no problems to maintain the equality.}) 23.
Bd5 (23. Bb3 fxe3) 23... fxe3 24. fxe3 Rfd8 25. Rxd8+ Rxd8 26. Bxb7 {, we have
transposition to the main line.}) 22... fxe3 23. fxe3 Rac8+ 24. Kb1 Rfd8 25.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 {This engdame is not deadly drawish but Back is by no means worse.}
26. Bxb7 (26. Bxf7 Kg7 $11) 26... Re8 ({Another option is} 26... Ne5 27. Nxe5
fxe5 28. Kc2 Bf5+ 29. e4 Be6 {White's pieces are a bit more active but the
