42,33]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5
Bxc5 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Rd1 {Nowadays this is the absolute main line. As we have
seen in the previous chapter, White's king is not completely safe on the
queenside. Therefore, White is planning to put pressure on the centre without
taking risks related to the safety of the king.} Qa5 10. a3 (10. Be2 {
transposes to 10.Rd1 from the previous chapter.}) ({As usual,} 10. Nd2 $2 {
runs into} e5 11. Bg5 d4 12. Nb3 Qb6 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black.})
10... Rd8 $5 {This move is analyzed until the very deep endgame nowadays. I
wouldn't suggest it but the subsequent analysis could be very useful for the
purposes of the comparison. After understanding the drawbacks of 10...Rd8, you
will understand the advantages of our main weapon - 10...Re8.} ({At some point,
Black's first choice was} 10... Be7 {Nowadays, it is known that White has more
than one way to achieve a comfortable position. Once again, I suggest that you
take a closer look at these lines. Even if you don't play them, the analysis
will help you to get a better feeling of the arising positions.} 11. Be2 ({
