previous chapter.}) 11... Ne4 $5 {This attempt to solve the problems by means
of simplifications does not work completely.} ({Another option is} 11... dxc4
12. Bxc4 Nh5 {Despite gaining the advantage of two bishops, Black's position
remains passive and cramped.} ({After} 12... e5 13. Bg3 Bg4 14. O-O $14 {
, White is better due to the weak d5-square and the vulnerable e5-pawn.}) ({
The thematic} 12... a6 13. O-O b5 {fails to solve Black's problems since White
can grab the initiative by means of} 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. Ne4 {A possible
continuation would be} g6 16. Nc5 Qb6 17. Nxb7 Qxb7 18. Qe2 $14 {White's
bishop pair gives him a stable advantage/}) 13. O-O Nxf4 14. exf4 {Such
positions are often bad for Black due to the problematic c8-bishop. Below, I
provide some sample lines in order to illustrate the typical ways of playing
in such positions.} g6 (14... Rd8 15. Rxd8+ Qxd8 16. Rd1 Qc7 {Black is forced
to spend one more tempo on moving the queen.} ({The problem is that} 16... Bd7
$2 {runs into} 17. f5 $1 {when White is achieving a huge advantage by force.}
Qe8 {The most tenacious continuation.} ({Worse is} 17... exf5 {since after} 18.
Qb3 Qe8 (18... Qc8 19. Bxf7+ Kh8 20. Qd5 $18) 19. Bxf7+ $1 Qxf7 20. Qxb7 $18 {
White is winning.}) ({After} 17... Qc8 $6 18. Qd3 Be8 19. fxe6 fxe6 20. Nd5 $1
Qd8 21. Qe2 {White is winning.}) 18. fxe6 Bxe6 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Qb3 Bf6 21.
Ne4 {Black's position remains very difficult due to the vulnerable king.}) 17.
Qe4 $14 {White is better. It is still not clear how Black will complete the
development.}) ({Another typical position would arise after} 14... Rb8 15. Rfe1
Rd8 16. Rxd8+ Qxd8 17. Rd1 Bd7 18. b4 a6 19. Ne4 $36 {[%cal Ge4g3,Gf4f5] The
activity of White's pieces and Black's poor coordination make the bishop pair
irrelevant. White is now planning to prepare the advance f4-f5 by means of Ng3.
}) 15. g3 a6 16. Ne4 b5 17. Be2 Qb6 18. Qc3 $14) 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 $1 ({
The other recapture is also possible but it is considered to be less dangerous
nowadays.} 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. bxc3 exd5 15. Rxd5 Bxa3 16. Nd4 $1 a5 (16... Nxd4
$6 17. exd4) 17. Rb5 (17. Kd2 a4 18. Rb5) 17... a4 18. Kd2 {This endgame is
approximately equal.}) 13... exd5 14. O-O $14 {There is still a lot of room to
analyse but overall White has more plesant play.}) ({The immediate} 10... Ne4
$6 {runs into} 11. cxd5 (11. b4 $2 Nxb4) 11... exd5 12. Rxd5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 $1
Qxa3 (13... Be6 $2 14. Ng5) 14. Ng5 $1 $40 {with a dangerous attack.}) 11. Nd2
(11. Be2 Ne4 12. O-O Nxc3 13. bxc3 h6 $11) 11... d4 {This move marks the
beginning of a forced sequence which is quite typical for this line.} 12. Nb3
Qb6 13. Na4 Bb4+ 14. axb4 Qxb4+ 15. Nd2 e5 16. Bg5 Qa5 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 17. Qb3
Nb4 {[%cal Gc8d7]} 18. Be2 ({Or first} 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Be2 Bd7) 18... Bd7 19.
Bxf6 gxf6 20. Ra1 dxe3 21. fxe3 b5 22. O-O bxa4 23. Qc3 f5 24. Nf3 f6 {
strangely enough all previous moves are almost forced} 25. Nh4 Nc6 26. Qa3 $1 {
Only now Black has some choice although it's hardly enough for a full equality.
} e4 ({The alternative} 26... Qd2 {fails to achieve a complete equality. For
example, after} 27. Rf2 Rab8 28. c5 Qb4 29. Nxf5 Qxa3 30. Rxa3 Na5 31. Bd3 Rb4
32. h3 $14 {White retains an advantage.}) ({An interesting attempt is} 26...
Rab8 $5 {when Black wants to make a draw in different kind of endgames but
