Nxe4 Bf8 21. Nd2 Nc5 {Black gets enough counterplay for the pawn. A possible
line would be:} 22. b4 Na4 23. Rc1 Nb2 24. O-O Qxa3 $11) 19... Rac8 20. O-O Bf8
({I also analyzed the ambitious} 20... f5 $5 21. Nd5 {I think White's chances
are slightly prefferable} Nc7 22. Bg3 Bf8 23. Nc3 Ne6 24. Bxe5 Rc5 25. Rd5 Qxc4
26. Qxc4 Rxc4 27. Rfd1 Rc5 28. Rxc5 {126} Nxc5 29. Rd5 {White has more active
pieces, but Black should be able to hold this endgame.}) 21. Qg4 (21. Bg3 Qxc4
22. Bxe5 Qxe2 23. Nxe2 Rc2 $11 {With this active rook on c2, Black has nothing
to worry about 1/2 (32) Urkedal, F (2545) -Galchenko, M (2395) Norway 2019})
21... Rxc4 $5 $146 {Vishy chose a different capture and was unable to equalize}
(21... Qxc4 22. Nxe4 Kh8 23. h3 $14 {The structure is symmetrical, but White's
pieces are more active and Black is unable to oppose along the "d" file
because the "d8" square is covered. White's advantage is not big, but
indisputable 1/2 (66) Mamedyarov, S (2804)-Anand, V (2767) Wijk aan Zee 2018})
22. Nd5 Kh8 23. Qh5 Kg8 24. Qxe5 Qc6 $1 {The idea is Nc7} 25. b3 Rc5 26. b4 Nc7
$1 27. Qxc7 {exchanging queens leads to an equal endgame after} (27. Nf6+ {
seems interesting, but it is not enough for an advantage} gxf6 28. Qg3+ Rg5 29.
Bxg5 fxg5 30. Qxg5+ (30. Rc1 Qh6 $1 $132 {is the idea which saves the day})
30... Bg7 31. Rc1 Qd5 $11 {Black's pieces are well coordinated}) 27... Qxc7 28.
Nxc7 Rxc7 29. g4 Rc3 30. Rd7 Rxa3 31. Rxb7 a5 32. b5 a4 33. Ra7 Rb3 $11 {
with a draw.}) 18... Qxd2+ 19. Rxd2 (19. Kxd2 f5 $1 {Black needs to play
active, before White coordinates his pieces} 20. Nxc5 Nxc5 21. f3 Rac8 22. Bh4
(22. e4 fxe4 23. Be3 Ne6 $11) 22... e4 23. b4 Nd3 {It seems risky for Black,
but my analysis shows that Black's strong knight and the weird position of
