Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Rd1 Qa5 10. a3 Re8 $1 11.
Nd2 e5 12. Bg5 Nd4 13. Qb1 Bf5 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Ne4 16. Ncxe4 {This is
the most popular move. In order to hold the balance, Black should play
precisely.} dxe4 17. Qxe4 Qb6 $1 {This is the only move that leaves Black in
the game.} (17... Nb3 $6 {is just bad after} 18. Qc2 Nxd2 19. Rxd2 $1 (19. Qxd2
Qa6 20. Qc2 f6 21. Bh4 Rac8 22. O-O Bf8 $11 {1/2 (43) Thybo,J (2479)-Vlahos,K 
(2306) Heraklion 2017}) 19... f6 (19... Bf8 {is also possible, but failed to
impress} 20. O-O Rec8 21. Rd7 $16) 20. Bh4 Rad8 21. Ke2 $1 $16 {Black doesn't
have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 18. Rb1 (18. b4 {looks like a natural
way to save the pawn, but then Black gets an active counterplay through a7-a5}
Bf8 19. Qd3 $1 ({If} 19. Nf3 $2 {Black gets counterplay by means of the
thematic} a5 20. c5 Nxf3+ $1 {The most precise move order.} (20... Qb5 21. Nxd4
exd4 22. Qd3 Qxd3 23. Rxd3 axb4 24. axb4 $11 {1/2 (53) Mesaros,F (2335)
-Zumsande,M (2467) Karlsruhe 2017}) 21. gxf3 Qb5 {In order to secure the
safety of his king, White should accept an inferior endgame.} 22. Qd3 Qxd3 23.
Rxd3 axb4 24. axb4 Ra4 $17 {White is going to lose his queenside pawns. At the
same time, he should take care of the bishop.}) 19... Ne6 20. Bh4 a5 {Once
again, this typical break works very well for Black. White cannot secure the
integrity of his queenside structure.} 21. c5 Qc6 22. O-O axb4 23. axb4 Ra4 $1
{Thanks to small trick black is equalizing by force} 24. Rb1 (24. Nc4 Rxb4 25.
Nxe5 Qc8 $5 26. Bg3 Nxc5 27. Qd5 Qe6 $11) 24... Nxc5 25. bxc5 Rxh4 26. g3 (26.
Rb6 Qxc5 27. Rxb7 Rb4 28. Rxb4 {1/2 (28) Kitaev,S (2356)-Wedel,L (2164) ICCF
email 2018}) 26... Ra4 27. Rb6 Qxc5 28. Rxb7 Rb4 $11) (18. Qb1 {it is
dangerous for White to move the queen far from the centre} Ne6 19. Bh4 Bxe3 $1
{This is the key idea. The sacrifice is working quite well for Black. I
analyzed this position in great detail. White survives, but in a practical
game, I would prefer Black.} 20. fxe3 Qxe3+ 21. Kf1 Qf4+ 22. Bf2 (22. Nf3 Qxc4+
$17) 22... Rad8 $1 {Black is not risking anything in all the lines} 23. g3 (23.
Qc2 e4 24. g3 Qh6 25. Nxe4 Qh3+ 26. Kg1 Nf4 27. gxf4 (27. Bd4 {is another
