Ng3 Rxd1+ 29. Kg2 Rxh1 30. Kxh1 h5 $36 {I think that Black is better here.})
23... Qh6 24. Ne4 (24. Qc2 Qh3+ 25. Kg1 Nf4 {s a forced draw} (25... f5 $5 {
is a move to continue the game} 26. c5 e4 $44) 26. gxf4 Qg4+ 27. Kf1 Qh3+ $11)
24... Qh3+ 25. Kg1 $4 (25. Ke1 $1 $13) 25... Nf4 $1 {0-1 (25) Tarjan,J (2479)
-Zumsande,M (2422) Douglas 2015}) 18... h6 19. Bh4 g5 $1 20. b4 (20. Bg3 {
is too passive to pose any problems} Rad8 21. exd4 (21. b4 $2 f5 $1 $19) 21...
exd4 22. Be5 Bd6 $11) 20... Bf8 21. Bg3 Rad8 22. exd4 (22. Rd1 $5 {is a
possible try for White} Bg7 $5 {I like this calm move. All Black's pieces are
well placed now. White can't castle because of the idea ...Ne2-c3. The arising
positions are quite sharp, but Black's initiative seems more than enough to
maintain the balance.} (22... f5 $5 {is a direct approach, which also works
here} 23. Qb1 f4 24. exd4 exd4+ 25. Kf1 fxg3 26. hxg3 d3 $44 {White's rook on
h1 is awkwardly placed}) 23. Qb1 Qc6 24. f3 e4 $1 25. fxe4 Nf5 26. Bf2 Nd6 $44)
22... exd4 23. Be5 Bg7 24. O-O (24. Nf3 Bxe5 25. Nxe5 Qd6 26. f4 gxf4 $11)
24... Rxe5 25. Qd3 {The position is calming down to an approximately equal
endgame. Black's pawn on d4 is blocked, but it is still quite strong. It is
