1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qc2
Nc6 9. Rd1 Qa5 10. a3 Re8 $1 11. Nd2 e5 12. Bg5 Nd4 13. Qb1 Bf5 14. Bd3 Bxd3
15. Qxd3 Ne4 16. Nxd5 $1 {This is the most principled continuation for White.
The position is indeed picturesque with those 3 knights in the centre. I don't
want to scare you, but it is the starting point of our analysis and probably
the most critical position for the database.} Nxg5 {Black should accept the
challenge and take the bishop} 17. b4 (17. exd4 $5 {An important alternative.
The arising positions are not that sharp as in the main line.} Bxd4 18. b4 $1 (
{If White decides to castles first} 18. O-O {then} Qd8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] is
strong. Black is planning the advance ...b7-b5.} 19. Qb3 (19. a4 {is stoping
b7-b5, but looks too slow to pose any problems} Ne6 20. Nf3 Bxb2 21. Rb1 Bd4
22. Rxb7 Rb8 $1 (22... Nc5 $4 23. Qf5 $1 Nxb7 24. Ng5 $18) 23. Rxb8 Qxb8 24. h3
h6 $11) (19. b4 b5 $1 20. Ne3 bxc4 21. Ndxc4 Rc8 $132 {without the strong
outpost on "d5", White has no hopes for an advantage.}) 19... Rc8 20. Rfe1 Ne6
21. Nf3 (21. a4 Qh4) 21... f6 $11 {White can't use the pin along the a2-g8
diagonal.}) 18... Qd8 19. Qb3 {by delaying the castle, White is ensuring the
strong outpost on d5 first} Ne6 $5 {I believe that this is the human choice} (
19... a5 $5 {Is also possible and my analysis shows that Black is OK, but it
is more complicated} 20. O-O a4 21. Qc2 b5 22. Ne3 (22. Nc3 {doesn't pose any
problems either} bxc4 23. Nxc4 Rc8 24. Nb5 Re6 $13) 22... bxc4 23. Ndxc4 Qf6 {
White's only chance is the passed "b" pawn, but Black's active pieces fully
compensate it. I analyzed a lot further, but all you need to know here is that
the position is playable for both sides and Black has at least equal chances.}
24. b5 (24. Nf5 h5 $5 (24... Rad8 $5 {is also possible} 25. b5 g6 26. Nfe3 {
should be about equal as well}) 25. h4 (25. Ncd6 Red8 26. h4 Ne6 27. Qe4 Ra6
28. Nb7 Bxf2+ $1 29. Kxf2 Rxd1 30. Rxd1 g6 {and Black wins the piece back}) (
25. b5 Rab8 {is fine for Black}) 25... Ne6 26. Ncd6 Red8 27. Qe4 Ra6 28. Nxd4
exd4 29. Nb7 Rc8 30. Nc5 Nxc5 31. bxc5 Rxc5 $11 {with an immediate draw}) 24...
Rec8 {looks risky for Black but engines are optimistic here.} 25. b6 Rab8 26.
Qxa4 Qe6 $1 27. Rb1 Ne4 (27... Bxe3 28. Nxe3 Rxb6 $11) 28. b7 Rc7 29. Qa8 Qe8
30. Qa6 Nc5 31. Qa5 Qd7 $11) 20. O-O Qd7 21. Nf3 Rad8 22. Rfe1 (22. a4 b6 $5 {
is better to stop White's pawns first} (22... f6 23. a5 Qf7 24. Qa2 Rd7 25.
Nxd4 Nxd4 26. f4 $14 {White is pressing and eventually won in 1-0 (35) Koneru,
H (2557)-Zatonskih,A (2431) Batumi 2018}) 23. Rd2 f6 24. Rfd1 Qf7 25. h3 Kh8
$132 {looks about equal to me}) 22... f6 23. Nc3 (23. Ne3 g6 $1 (23... Qf7 $6
24. Nf5 $14) 24. Nc2 Kg7 25. h3 b6 $11) 23... Qf7 24. Ne2 Bb6 25. c5 Bc7 $132 {
A typical situation where White has three against two on the queenside and Black
has a kingside majority. The fight will be who will start rolling his pawns
first. The bishop on c7 is perfectly placed and Black is ready to continue
with ...f7-f5 and ...e5-e4 soon.}) 17... Qd8 18. bxc5 Nde6 {This is an
important crossroad. White should decide to play more positional or more
concrete.} 19. O-O (19. Qf5 $5 {Caruana's choice is very sharp and the price
of each move is quite high.} Nxc5 20. h4 Nge6 21. Nf3 Qa5+ 22. Ke2 f6 23. h5 {
we are following the game Caruana - Nakamura} e4 24. Nd2 (24. h6 {looks scary
but leads only to perpetual after the forced sequence of moves:} exf3+ 25. gxf3
g6 26. Rhg1 Qxa3 27. Rxg6+ hxg6 28. Qxg6+ Kh8 29. Qxf6+ Kh7 $11) 24... Ng5 $1 {
only move.} ({Caruana won a good game thanks to his brilliant preparation} 
24... Qxa3 $2 25. Rh4 Rad8 26. Nxe4 Qa2+ 27. Ke1 Qa5+ 28. Kf1 $18 Nxe4 29. Rxe4
Qa4 30. Rb1 Ng5 31. Rd4 Nf7 32. Rxb7 Qa6 33. Qb1 Rf8 34. Kg1 Kh8 35. c5 Rc8 36.
Nf4 Ne5 37. h6 g6 38. Rd6 Qc4 39. Re6 Rxc5 40. Ree7 {1-0 (40) Caruana,F (2819)
-Nakamura,H (2754) Zagreb 2019}) 25. f4 (25. h6 {again this move is not giving
White anything} Re5 26. Qg4 Rxd5 27. cxd5 Qa6+ 28. Ke1 Nd3+ 29. Kf1 Nb2+ 30.
Kg1 Nxd1 31. Qxd1 Qd3 $132 {and I prefer Black}) 25... exf3+ 26. gxf3 Qxa3 {
We are going too deep, but I expect many more games in this line. And most of
them will follow Caruana's footsteps. I analyze in this position 4 different
options for White. Everywhere the position remains double-edged.} (26... Re5 $5
27. Qc2 Qa6 28. Nf1 Rae8 29. Rh4 $5 {the positon is quite complex but I would
prefer White}) 27. f4 ({Insufficient is} 27. Ra1 Qb2 28. Rhb1 ({After} 28. Qb1
{Black should avoid exchanging the queens and keep the tension. White's king
is quite vulnerable in this position.} Qd4 29. Ra3 Nxf3 30. Kxf3 Qxd2 31. Ra2
Qd3 32. Qxd3 Nxd3 33. Nc7 Ne5+ $11) 28... Qd4 29. f4 Rad8 $1 {Black is
preparing the move ...Rdd5 under favourable circumstances.} (29... Nf7 30. Ra3
$40) 30. fxg5 (30. Ra3 Nf3 $1 {only move but what a brilliant one! Now, White
should force the draw.} 31. Kxf3 Qxd2 32. Nxf6+ gxf6 33. Rg1+ Kf7 34. Qxc5 (34.
Qxh7+ $4 Ke6 $19) 34... Rg8 35. Raa1 Qd7 $11 {The position is equal.}) 30...
Re5 {An important move. It is important to get access to the d3-square.} 31.
Qf4 Qd3+ 32. Ke1 Rdxd5 {We see the point behind 29...Rad8!} 33. cxd5 Rxe3+ 34.
Kd1 Qe2+ 35. Kc2 Qd3+ 36. Kc1 Re1+ 37. Kb2 Re2 38. Qb8+ Kf7 $11) ({The
aggressive} 27. h6 {runs into} Re5 $1 {[%cal Ga8e8] followed by ...Rae8.} 28.
Qc2 Rae8 29. Nf1 Nce6 {Another important resource. The knight is heading for
f4.} 30. Kf2 ({Another thematic motif can be seen after} 30. Rh4 Nc7 $1 {
[%csl Rd5] Deflecting the central d5-knight.} 31. Rd3 Qc5 32. Qb3 Nf7 33. Rg4
Rg5 34. Rxg5 fxg5 35. hxg7 Nxd5 36. Rxd5 Qc7 $13 {It might turn out that the
white king is more vulnerable than the black one.}) 30... Nf4 $1 {Of course,
it's not easy to remember all the subtleties in this computer-like position}
31. Nxf4 Rxe3 32. Rh4 (32. Rd3 Rxf3+ 33. Kg2 Rxd3 $11) 32... Rxf3+ 33. Kg2 Rxf4
34. Rxf4 Qh3+ 35. Kf2 Qxh6 $44) ({To a forced draw leads.} 27. Rhg1 Rad8 28.
Nxf6+ (28. h6 Re6 $13) 28... gxf6 29. Rxg5+ fxg5 30. Qxg5+ Kf7 31. Qf5+ Ke7 32.
Qxh7+ Ke6 $11 {with a perpetual to follow.}) 27... Nce4 28. Rhg1 Nc3+ 29. Nxc3
Qxc3 30. Rg3 Rad8 $1 31. fxg5 Re5 32. Qf4 (32. Qg4 Qd3+ 33. Kf2 fxg5 $44) 32...
fxg5 33. Rxg5 Qd3+ 34. Kf2 Rxg5 35. Qxg5 h6 36. Qg4 (36. Qe7 a5 $44) 36... a5
$1 {finally we have a position that could be evaluated by intuition. Despite
being a piece down, Black has enough counterplay thanks to the passed pawn and
the king safety.} 37. Qe2 Qd7 38. Ke1 Qh3 39. Qf3 Qh4+ 40. Ke2 Qh2+ 41. Qf2
Qxh5+ 42. Nf3 Rxd1 43. Kxd1 a4 $11) ({Harmless is} 19. Nb3 {which is well met
by} Nxc5 20. Nxc5 Qa5+ 21. Qc3 Qxc5 22. Qb4 Rac8 23. Qxb7 Qa5+ 24. Qb4 Qxb4+
25. axb4 Rxc4 $11 {with a drawish endgame. 1/2 (35) Zhou,J (2608)-Fedorowicz,J
(2420) Philadelphia 2019}) 19... Nxc5 20. Qb1 {Black should play very
accurately in this position} Nge6 {Strategically speaking the position is
equal: Both sides have very strong outposts on d5 and c5 respectively. Black's
aim is to calm down White's activity.} 21. Qf5 $5 ({After} 21. Nf3 {Black's
most precise reaction is} Nf8 $1 {It turns out that White cannot exploit the
opposition along the d-file.} 22. Rd2 (22. Qf5 $5 Qc8 23. Qh5 f6 24. Nh4 Kh8
$132) 22... Rc8 23. Rfd1 Qd6 24. Nc3 Qg6 25. Rd5 (25. Qb4 e4 26. Nd4 h6 27. h3
b6 28. Nde2 Nfe6 $13) 25... Qxb1 26. Rxb1 f6 $11 {with equality in 1/2 (42)
Aronian,L (2764)-Nakamura,H (2769) Stavanger 2018}) 21... f6 22. Nb1 (22. h4
Qc8 $1 23. h5 Ng5 24. Qc2 Qg4 $132) (22. Nf3 Qc8 23. Nh4 Nf8 $11) 22... Na4 $1
{Otherwise, it's not easy to handle white's initiative} (22... Kh8 23. Nbc3 Qc8
24. h4 $36) 23. Qc2 (23. Nbc3 Nxc3 24. Nxc3 Qe7 {with only one pair of knights
Black's position is solid.} 25. Nb5 b6 26. Rd5 Rad8 27. Rfd1 Rxd5 28. cxd5 Nc5
29. a4 Rd8 $11) (23. h4 Nb2 $1 24. Rc1 Nxc4 25. Rfd1 Nd6 26. Qg4 f5 27. Qb4 a5
28. Qb3 Kh8 $13) (23. Qg4 Nec5 24. Nbc3 Nxc3 25. Nxc3 Qe7 26. Rd5 b6 $11) 23...
Qa5 $5 (23... Nec5 {Black was slightly worse, but holds in the recent
correspondance game} 24. Nbc3 Nxc3 25. Nxc3 Qa5 26. Rd5 Red8 27. Qd1 Qc7 28.
Nb5 Qb6 29. h3 a6 30. Nc3 Rac8 31. Qd2 $14 {1/2 (37) Joppich,U (2477)-Binas,J 
